metadata.name: Algorithm, be my guide #150
metadata.description:
At length, I summoned the courage to approach.

-

I was worn. Months of aimless wandering have culminated in this series; a meditation on my struggles to find a direction in my life and with my art.

At times paralyzed by too many possibilities, and at other times completely void of ideas. I was lost in the depths of my thinking, overwhelmed by indecision and doubt.

Generative works are a form of process art, yet along the way I’d forgotten to “trust the process”. It was time to cede control and let each line of code light the way.

-

This project paints on a 2D canvas, pixel by pixel. I used a custom projection that blends isometric and perspective techniques, to create an uncanny viewpoint between the two. Objects are randomly generated, then an algorithm applies color mixing and position displacement to each pixel as it’s rendered.

By default the canvas has 2k pixels on its longest edge. You can change this in live view by pressing any number from 1-9. For example, pressing ‘4’ would render it with 4k pixels along the longest edge. I recommend ‘4’, but this can take up to a few minutes to render.

Press ‘s’ to save the rendered image.

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #117
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: Hexaëder #183
metadata.description:
Hexaëder (cube) is a research into abstraction and a search for a balance between simplification and visual complexity.

No matter how simple and unambiguous things appear to be, in reality they are often more complex. Enjoy the simple, explore the complex.

Hexaeder has a wide variety of possible outcomes. I have put together 10 different color palettes; the number of cubes ranges from 10 to 401 (18 different grids); each cell can have 4 different background patterns; each cube can be filled in 4 distinct ways; there are 5 line colors and 16 different "cube figures"; the vignette can be black or be the color of the palette, and there are several "texture settings". This results in over 1.8 million possibilities.

For more information see: https://www.behance.net/gallery/131114761/Hexaeder-Flattened-cubes

metadata.name: DeStijl Fortunes #125
metadata.description:
The best part of being full and happy and ready to leave the restaurant is opening the fortune cookie. Does it mean something? Does it have poor grammar and vague references? You know it's not really *for you* but it sure feels like it.
This collab between sgt_slaughtermelon and 0xphiiil creates simple pleasant DeStijl-influenced designs determined by your hash and inspired by Theo Van Doesburg that feature crypto-centric fortunes. Maybe they'll give you some *not financial advice* or maybe it will be a vague truism or an optimistic or pessimistic omen. Who knows? Part of the fun is imagining that it's for you and it's real - and if you don't like it, just open another cookie.

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #222
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: twofiftythousand #58
metadata.description:
twofiftythousand is about the chaos of unlimited decisions. Look for a pattern in the noise.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

metadata.name: Cubick (Summer) #11
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender Renders.

Best viewed in live mode.

In each output, the four "cubes" are arranged in the same calming, 'zen-like' formation.

In each output, the orientation of the "cubes", and the number and positions of the colored regions varies.

All outputs in this collection will have the same color palette (called Summer).

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1375x1500px PNG.

Several "Cubick" collections will be released, each with a different color palette.

metadata.description:
Thank you for collecting my art, it means a lot to me as an Artist, you are investing in me and your investment will help me to create, explore, live and learn.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution PNG at 2000 x 2625 px.

Feel free to DM me anytime on Twitter @lessliexyz.
